  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. Global Standards and Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\n2. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border financial transaction monitoring\n- Asset tracing and seizure mechanisms\n\n3. Jurisdictional Cooperation\n- Information sharing between national financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements\n- Coordinated investigations of international financial crimes\n- Mutual legal assistance in criminal matters\n\n4. Legal Harmonization\n- Standardizing definitions of money laundering\n- Establishing consistent legal frameworks\n- Aligning prosecution and enforcement strategies\n- Creating common reporting and compliance standards\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Coordinated law enforcement actions\n- Financial institution oversight\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Technology and Digital Challenges\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Cyber financial crime prevention\n- International data sharing protocols\n- Emerging technological compliance strategies\n\nThese intersections create complex, multilayered approaches to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
